[{"location":"","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"CurrentModule = TwoPointFunctions","category":"page"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.jl","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.jl","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Reference","title":"Reference","text":"Modules = [TwoPointFunctions]","category":"page"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.cosχ","text":"cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nCosine of the angle between the unit vectors denoted by the spherical coordinates  (theta_1phi_1) and (theta_2phi_2). This is equivalent to the cosine of the  angular distance along a great circle between these two points on a sphere.\n\nNumerically this is given by\n\ncoschi((theta_1phi_1) (theta_1phi_1)) = cos(theta_1)cos(theta_2) + \nsin(theta_1)sin(theta_2)cos(phi_1 - phi_2)\n\nThe unicode character at the end of the function's name is \\chi, and not x.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n1.0\n\njulia> cosχ((0,0), (pi,0))\n-1.0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂²θ₁cosχ-Tuple{Any,Any}","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂²θ₁cosχ","text":"∂²θ₁cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nSecond derivative of cosχ with respect to θ₁.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂²θ₁cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n-1.0\n\njulia> ∂²θ₁cosχ((0,0), (pi,0))\n1.0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂²θ₂cosχ-Tuple{Any,Any}","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂²θ₂cosχ","text":"∂²θ₂cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nSecond derivative of cosχ with respect to θ₂.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂²θ₂cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n-1.0\n\njulia> ∂²θ₂cosχ((0,0), (pi,0))\n1.0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂²ϕ₁cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂²ϕ₁cosχ","text":"∂²ϕ₁cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nSecond derivative of cosχ with respect to ϕ₁.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂²ϕ₁cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n-0.0\n\njulia> ∂²ϕ₁cosχ((pi/2,0), (pi/2, 0))\n-1.0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂²ϕ₂cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂²ϕ₂cosχ","text":"∂²ϕ₂cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nSecond derivative of cosχ with respect to ϕ₂.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂²ϕ₂cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n-0.0\n\njulia> ∂²ϕ₂cosχ((pi/2,0), (pi/2, 0))\n-1.0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₁cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₁cosχ","text":"∂θ₁cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nPartial derivative of cosχ with respect to θ₁.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂θ₁cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n0.0\n\njulia> ∂θ₁cosχ((0,0), (pi/2,0))\n1.0\n\nSee also: ∂θ₂cosχ\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₁∂θ₂cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₁∂θ₂cosχ","text":"TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₁∂θ₂cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nMixed derivative of cosχ with respect to θ₁ and θ₂. \n\nExamples\n\njulia> TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₁∂θ₂cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n1.0\n\njulia> TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₁∂θ₂cosχ((0,0), (pi,0))\n-1.0\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₂cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂θ₂cosχ","text":"∂θ₂cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nPartial derivative of cosχ with respect to θ₂.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂θ₂cosχ((0,0), (0,0))\n0.0\n\njulia> ∂θ₂cosχ((0,0), (pi/2,pi/2))\n-1.0\n\nSee also: ∂θ₁cosχ \n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂ϕ₁cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂ϕ₁cosχ","text":"∂ϕ₁cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nPartial derivative of cosχ with respect to ϕ₁.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂ϕ₁cosχ((pi/2, 0), (pi/2, pi/3)) ≈ sin(pi/3)\ntrue\n\njulia> ∂ϕ₁cosχ((pi/2, 0), (pi/2, pi/2))\n1.0\n\nSee also: ∂ϕ₂cosχ\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∂ϕ₂cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∂ϕ₂cosχ","text":"∂ϕ₂cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nPartial derivative of cosχ with respect to ϕ₂.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∂ϕ₂cosχ((pi/2, 0), (pi/2, pi/3)) ≈ -sin(pi/3)\ntrue\n\njulia> ∂ϕ₂cosχ((pi/2, 0), (pi/2, pi/2))\n-1.0\n\nSee also: ∂ϕ₁cosχ\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∇ϕ₁cosχ-Tuple{Tuple{#s23,#s24} where #s24<:Real where #s23<:Real,Tuple{#s25,#s26} where #s26<:Real where #s25<:Real}","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∇ϕ₁cosχ","text":"∇ϕ₁cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nThe hatphi_1 component of nabla_1 cos chi in the spherical polar basis. Numerically this is equivalent to \n\nnabla phi_1 coschi ((theta_1 phi_1) (theta_2 phi_2)) = \nfrac1sin(theta_1) partial phi_1 coschi ((theta_1 phi_1) (theta_2 phi_2))\n\nexcept ∇ϕ₁cosχ is defined to avoid coordinate singularities at the poles.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∇ϕ₁cosχ((0, 0), (0, 0))\n-0.0\n\njulia> ∇ϕ₁cosχ((pi/2, 0), (pi/2, pi/2))\n1.0\n\nSee also: ∂ϕ₁cosχ, ∇ϕ₂cosχ\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∇ϕ₂cosχ-Tuple{Tuple{#s15,#s14} where #s14<:Real where #s15<:Real,Tuple{#s13,#s12} where #s12<:Real where #s13<:Real}","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∇ϕ₂cosχ","text":"∇ϕ₂cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nThe hatphi_2 component of nabla_2 cos chi in the spherical polar basis. Numerically this is equivalent to \n\nnabla phi_2 coschi ((theta_1 phi_1) (theta_2 phi_2)) = \nfrac1sin(theta_2) partial phi_2 coschi ((theta_1 phi_1) (theta_2 phi_2))\n\nexcept ∇ϕ₂cosχ is defined to avoid coordinate singularities at the poles.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∇ϕ₂cosχ((0, 0), (0, 0))\n0.0\n\njulia> ∇ϕ₂cosχ((pi/2, 0), (pi/2, pi/2))\n-1.0\n\nSee also: ∂ϕ₂cosχ, ∇ϕ₁cosχ\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∇₁cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∇₁cosχ","text":"∇₁cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nReturn  (hattheta_1 cdot nabla_1 cos chi hatphi_1 cdot nabla_1 cos chi), where nabla_1 represents  the gradient on the unit sphere with respect to (theta_1 phi_1).\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∇₁cosχ((0,0), (pi/2, pi/3)) == (cos(pi/3), sin(pi/3))\ntrue\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#TwoPointFunctions.∇₂cosχ","page":"Reference","title":"TwoPointFunctions.∇₂cosχ","text":"∇₂cosχ((θ₁,ϕ₁), (θ₂,ϕ₂))\n\nReturn  (hattheta_2 cdot nabla_2 cos chi  hatphi_2 cdot nabla_2 cos chi), where nabla_2 represents  the gradient on the unit sphere with respect to (theta_2 phi_2).\n\nExamples\n\njulia> ∇₂cosχ((0,0), (pi/2, pi/3))\n(-1.0, -0.0)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"}]
